Organic Chemistry






ORGANIC CHEMISTRY

This is an aspect of chemistry that deals with the study of naturally occurring matter.

Organic chemistry deals with the study of the composition, properties, production, uses and effects of organic compounds.

Organic compounds are compounds of Carbon with the exception of Carbon IV oxide, Carbon II oxide, Carbonates, Hydrogen carbonates and carbides. For instance, CO2, CO, MgCO3, Ca(HCO3), CaC2 and so on are not organic compounds and whereas they are Carbon compounds. Apart from these sets of Carbon compounds mentioned, every other compounds of Carbon are organic compounds.

Organic compounds contain Carbon as the major element, other elements include: Hydrogen, Oxygen, Sulphur, Silicon, Nitrogen, Phosphorus and Halogens (i.e. Fluorine, Chlorine, bromine and iodine).

It should be noted that organic compounds that contain Carbon and Hydrogen only are called HYDROCARBONS. Hence, all hydrocarbons are organic compounds, But not all organic compounds are hydrocarbons.

At this point, the question is why Carbon? I mean why it must be Carbon being the major element in organic compounds, why not other elements.

The answer is because of unique properties of Carbon. Hence, this takes us to the unique nature of Carbon.


Unique Nature of Carbon

Carbon is a non-metallic element located on Group 4, period 2 of the periodic table with atomic number of 6. Carbon doesn't get itself involved in electrovalent bonding, But rather covalent bonding since it can neither loose nor gain electrons.

Electronic configuration and energy level diagram of Carbon is as shown below:

So, the unique properties of Carbon are:

(i)     Excitation

(ii)     Catenation

(iii)     Hybridization


Excitation

This is the process whereby an electron jumps from a lower energy orbital to a higher energy orbital. Excitation takes place in Carbon when one electron jumps from the 2S-orbital to the 2Pz orbital. Thereafter, the Carbon is said to be in its excited state.

Cartenation

This is the ability of an element to form multiple bonds among itself to form a long chain. The chain could be straight or branched. Carbon is the only element that demonstrates this property, For Carbon to catenate; it must be in its excited state not ground state.

It is as illustrated below:




Hybridization

This is the mixing or blending of orbitals to form some set of new identical orbitals called Hybrid orbitals. When orbitals of nearby equal quantum levels blend together to form hybrid orbitals, the phenomenon is said to be Hybridization.

This occurs in Carbon when it is in its excited state, the 2S orbital blends with the 2Ps orbitals. The 2S-orbital could blend with 2Px, 2Py and 2Pz, it could be with just 2Px and 2Py only, and also it could be with only 2Px. Hence, hybridization is sub-divided into THREE types.

(i)     Sp3 hybridization

(ii)     Sp2 hybridization

(iii)     Sp hybridization

SP3 Hybridization

This involves the blending of one s-orbital with three p-orbitals. In excited Carbon atom, SP3 hybridization takes place when 2S1 blends with 2Px1, 2Py1 and 2Pz1 to form SP3 hybrid orbitals. When this happens, the Carbon atom is said to be SP3 hybridized Carbon atom. It is as illustrated below;

The following are properties of SP3 hybridization

·     It requires the blending of one s-orbital and three p-orbitals

·     It leads to the formation of four hybrid orbitals

·     It leads to the formation of saturated organic molecules

·     It leads to the formation of Carbon to Carbon single bond

·     It leads to the formation of a molecule which is tetrahedral in shape

·     It leads to the formation of a molecule with bond length of 1.5Ao and bond angle of 109o28' or 109.5o

·     It is found in alkanes and their derivatives. E.g.: Propane, 2,2-dimethylheptane, 3-iodooctane and so on.

Spatial structure of Methane               C 1.5A C

SP2 Hybridization

This involves the blending of one s-orbital with two p-orbitals. In excited Carbon atom, sp2 hybridization takes place when 2s1 blends with 2Px1 and 2Py1 to form SP2 hybrid orbitals leaving 2Pz1 unhybridized with. The Carbon atom is said to be sp2 hybridized Carbon atom, and the unhybridized one electron is used for chemical reaction.

It is as illustrated below:


The following are properties of SP2 hybridization

·     It requires the blending of one s-orbital and two p-orbitals

·     It leads to the formation of three hybrid orbital

·     It leads to the formation of unsaturated organic molecules due to the presence of one unhybridized electron.

·     It leads to the formation of Carbon to Carbon double bond.

·     It leads to the formation of a molecule which is planar in shape

·     It leads to the formation of a molecule with bond length of 1.4Ao and bond angle of 120o.

·     It is found in alkenes and their derivatives E.g.: Butane, 2-methylpentene, 2-chloro-3-methylhexane, etc.

Spatial structure of Ethane

SP Hybridization

This involves the blending of one s-orbital with one p-orbital. In excited Carbon atom, SP hybridization takes place when 2S1 blends with 2Px1 to form SP hybrid orbitals leaving 2Py1 and 2Pz1 unhybridized Carbon atom, and the unhybridized two electrons are used for chemical reaction. Compounds of SP hybridized Carbon atoms are more reactive compare to those of SP2, while those of Sp3 are not even reactive at all. It is as illustrated below:

The following are the properties of SP hybridization:

·     It requires the blending of one s-orbital and one p-orbital

·     It leads to the formation of two hybrid orbitals

·     It leads to the formation of unsaturated organic molecules with a very high degree of unsaturation due to the presence of two unhybridized electrons.

·     It leads to the formation of Carbon to Carbon triple bond.

·     It leads to the formation of a molecule which is linear in shape.

·     It leads to the formation of a molecule with bond length of 1.33Ao and bond angle of 180o.

·     It is found in alkynes and their derivatives. E.g. Hexyne, 3-iodohept-2-yne, 2,3-dimethylBut-2-yne.

Structure of Ethyne

* It should be noted that Benzene and other aromatic compounds contain Sp3 and Sp2 hybridized Carbon atoms. E.g. Benzene itself, toluene, benzoic acid and so on.

Formulae used in Organic Chemistry

Basically, there are Four formulae used in organic chemistry. They include:

·     Empiricalformula               - Molecular formula

·     Structural formula          - Condensed formula

Empirical Formular

This is the formula that shows the simplest ratio of combination of the elements in a given organic compound.

For instance, Ethane is C2H4, it is seen that 2 is a common factor. Hence, the empirical formula of Ethane CH2.

The table below shows the Empirical formula of some organic compounds.

Empiricalformula can be calculated when percentage compositions of each elements in the compound are given. And also it could be mass instead of percentage composition. You do this using the normal procedure for getting empirical formula. It is as illustrated below:

Question 2

A hydrocarbon contains 90% Carbon. Determine its empirical formula. [C = 12, H = 1]

Solution

It contains Carbon and Hydrogen only since the question said it is Hydrocarbon

Elements CH
% compositions90%(100 90)% = 10%
Mole ratio7.510
11.33

Here, you need to be very careful in that you must not just approximate 1.33 to 1, the range is too much. You can only approximate when it is so close. Then in this case, you have to correct to the best fit fraction. For 1.33, the best fit fraction is 4/3

So, C: H is 1 : 4/3 which is 3 : 4

Hence, the empirical formula is C3H4.


Molecular Formula

This is the formula that shows the actual ratio of combination of elements in a given organic compound.

For instance, Ethane is C2H4 which is simply its molecular formula.

Molecular formula can be determined from empirical formula when the relative molecular mass of the compound is given. At times, vapour density is given instead of the relative molecular mass. The relation below can be used:

Relative Molecular Mass = Vapour Density x 2

The difference between empirical formula and a molecular formula is a common factor (n).

So, Molecular formula = (Empiricalformula)n

The value of n can be gotten from mass calculations.


Question 3

An organic compound has empirical formula CH2 and relative molecular mass of 42g/mol. The molecular formula of the organic compound is

Solution

Molecular formula = (Empirical formula)n

i.e. Molecular formula is (CH2)n

So, the mass of (CH2)n = 42 to get the value of n.

(1x12 + 2x1)n = 42

14n = 42

n = 3

The molecular formula is (CH2)­3­ = C3H6


Question 4

2.6g of a hydrocarbon contains 0.2g of Hydrogen. If its vapour density is 39. The molecular formula of the hydrocarbon is [C = 12, H = 1]

Solution

Here, Empirical formula needs to be determined before anyother procedure.

Mass of Hydrocarbon = 2.6g

If mass of Hydrogen = 0.2g, then mass of Carbon = 2.6g 0.2g

= 2.4g

`

Elements CH
Mass2.4g0.2g
Mole ratio0.2
11

Hence, the empirical formula is CH

Given vapour density to be 39, Relative Molecular mass is

R.M.M = V.D x 2

R.M.M = 39 x 2 = 78

Let, Molecular formula be (CH)n

Mass of (CH)n = 78g

(12x1 + 1x1)n = 78

13n = 78

n = 6.

Hence, the molecular formula of the hydrocarbon is C6H6.

This is the formula that shows all existing bonds between the elements in a given organic compounds. Due to the tetravalent nature of Carbon, Carbon must possess 4 bonds, while other attaching elements such as Oxygen (2bonds), Nitrogen (3 bonds). Homologous Series

These are group of organic compounds which follow regular structural pattern in which each successive member differs from each other by CH2 group.

A member of a particular homologous series is called Homologous.

Homologous series name is like a family name to some set of organic compounds. Members of a particular homologous series usually undergo similar chemical reactions due to the same functional group they possessed.

Functional group can be defined as a bond (single, double or triple), an atom, group of atoms or radicals which is common to every members of a particular homologous series in which it is the one that determine the chemical properties of the series.

A member of a particular homologous series can be converted to its immediate next member through a process called Homologation. It is usually a chemical reaction whereby the product exceeds the reactant by CH2 group.

The following are the properties / characteristics of homologous series:

1.     Members of a particular homologous series do follow a regular structural pattern.

2.     Each successive members of a particular homologous series differ from each other by CH2 group.

3.     Members of a particular homologous series do have a common functional group.

4.     Each successive members of a particular homologous series differ from each other by a molar mass of 14g/mol

5.     Members of a particular homologous series do have similar chemical properties.

6.     Members of a particular homologous series do have similar methods of preparation

7.     Members of a particular homologous series do show variation in their physical properties due to variation in number of Carbon atoms

8.     Members of the same homologous series do have the same type of hybridized Carbon atoms.

It should be noted that for a particular organic compound, the prefix tells the number of Carbon atoms it possessed, while the suffix tells the homologous series it belongs. If n represent number of Carbon, alk-is used to represent the collective name, while the individual name is as shown thus:

Alkylhalide(Also known as Haloalkanes)

From the above table, alkylhalides are generally represented as RX, where R is an alkyl group and X is an halogen group.

An Alkyl is obtained when an alkane loses one Hydrogen atom. Alkyl groups do not usually exist alone as organic compounds, But they are usually used as substituents (i.e. attachments). It is generally denoted as "R" with general molecular formula CnH2n+1 where n ≥ 1

When n = 1          When n = 2          When n = 3          When n = 6

Methyl (CH3-)     Ethyl (C2H5 - )     Propyl (C3H7 - )     Hexyl (C6H13-)

And so on.

So, in Alkylhalides, the one Hydrogen removed from Alkane to form Alkyl will be replaced with a halogen member which is usually Fluorine, Chloride, Iodine or Bromine. Hence, they are otherwise called Haloalkanes.

For instance, CH3Br is Methylbromide or Bromomethane C2H5I is Ethyliodide or Iodoethane, C3H7Cl is Propyl chloride or Chloropropane, C4H9F is Butylfluoride or FluoroButane.

From the above table, the alkanoic acids are usually represented as CnH2n + 1COOH, where n ≥ 0. And has its functional group to be COOH.

The same principles applied to Alkanal are also applicable here.

Do you even know why? (It is because Carbon is part of the functional group).

So, without wasting time, HCOOH is Methanoic acid CH3COOH is Ethanoic acid, C3H7COOH is Butanoic acid. So, can you derive Hexanoic acid?

Okay, Hex means n = 6 oic acid means it is a member of alkanoic acid (CnH2n + 1COOH)

But n = 5 for Hexanoic acid since 1 Carbon atom is part of the functional group.

Therefore, Hexanoic acid is C5H2(5) + 1COOH ≡ C5H11COOH

Arenes

These are aromatic hydrocarbons gotten from combination of Benzene ring laterally. It has the general molecular formula C4n + 2H2n + 4, where n ≥ 1. When n = 1, the compound is called Benzene (C6H6).

Benzene was first discovered by an English Physicist and Chemist called Micheal Faraday.

Nomenclature of Organic Compounds

This has to do with naming of organic compounds according to the IUPAC standard.

When a given compound is to be named, it is either you are given the structural formula or the condensed formula. You need to differentiate between the substituents (i.e the attachments) and the root compound.

The following are the procedures to be followed in naming organic compounds.

1. You identify the longest Carbon chain, it could be a straight chain or a branched chain.

Also you should know that when a Carbon atom is attached to the last Carbon, it should be counted as part of the longest Carbon chain.


2. The number of longest Carbon (i.e number of Carbons in the longest chain) determines the prefix of the root name, while the functional group present tells the suffix.

Five Carbons, with Carbon to Carbon single bond,

Root name is Pentane

Six Carbons, with Carbon to Carbon double bond

Root name is Hexane.

3. After which the longest chain has been identified; every other attachments apart from Hydrogen is taken as substituent(s)


2 substituents (two Methyl)

                         

3 substituents (one chloro, one Methyl and one Ethyl)

          

3 substituents (two iodo and one chloro)


4. Then number the Carbon atoms in both directions and consider the direction that gives less value for the Carbon functional group position and likewise the substituents.

Moving from left to right the Functional group is on the Second Carbon (2) Moving from Right to Left, the Functional group is on the Third Carbon (3) since 2 is Lesser than 3, then follow Left to Right.


Five Carbons makes it PentCarbon to Carbon double bond makes it ene.

Hence, the name is Pent 2 ene.

     

There are four substituents. Follow Left to Right numbering, there are substituents on 2, 3, 4, 4. Follow Right to Left numbering, There are substituents on 2, 2, 3, 4.

From their additions, Left to Right is 13, while Right to Left is 11.Then we consider Right to Left.

5. Substituents must be named before the root compound, and during the course, use comma (,) between numbers and use hypen (-) between a number and an alphabet.

From above, 2,2-dichloro      3-Ethyl          4-Methyl

It should be noted that substituents must be named in alphabetical order. So, the above compound will be named as 2,2 dichloro 3 ethyl 4 Methylpentane.

LR gives the functional groupPosition of 1.

RL gives functional groupPosition of 3

Isomerism

This is a phenomenon whereby two or more organic compounds have the same molecular formulaBut different structural formula.

Compounds with the same molecular formula But different structures are called Isomers. It was noticed that isomers are better identified when they have exactly the same type of elements (i.e the same number of Carbon, Hydrogen, Oxygen, halogens and so on).

A chemical reaction whereby an isomer is formed from another isomer such that both reactant and product have exactly the same atoms is called Isomerization.

In conclusion, isomerism is the phenomenon, isomers are those compounds and isomerization is the reaction.


Types of Isomerism

There are two major types of isomerism which are: Structural Isomerismand Steroisomerism.

Structural Isomerism

This is a type of isomerism whereby the structural pattern of the compounds differentiates between them. They still conform to the same molecular formula. It is sub-divided into four various types.

·     Chain isomerism

·     Position isomerism

·     Metamerism

·     Functional group isomerism

Chain Isomerism

Chain isomers do have the same molecular formular and they usually have the same chemical properties since they are members of the same homologous series. But the difference in their structures is usually as a result of the chain pattern.

Chain isomerism is usually explained using the alkanes.

Methane, Ethane and Propane do not have isomers, But other higher alkanes do undergo chain isomerism.

For Butane (2 isomers)C4H10

n-Butane (CH3CH2CH2CH3)     

2-Methylpropane (CH3CH(CH­­­­­3)CH3)

For Pentane (3 isomers)

n pentane

2-MethylButane

     

2, 2 dimetyl propane

For Hexane (5 isomers)

n-Hexane



2-Methylpentane

3-Methylpentane

     

2, 2, dimethylButane               

     

2,3-dimethylButane

It should be noted that isomers do have different IUPAC Nomenclature, there is no way two different isomers will have exactly the same name. If such happen, then they shouldn't be considered as isomers.

Position isomers are explained in alkene, alkyne, Alkylhalide, alkanol and so on. Even the para, meta and ortho compounds of Benzene- derived compounds are position isomers. Examples are as shown below.

Metamerism

This type of structural isomerism is usually exhibited by those organic compounds with two attaching alkyl groups to the functional group. Examples are alkoxyl, alkanoate and alkanone. This occurs when the attaching alkyl groups are being interchanged. Metamers do belong to the same homologous series, hence they usually have the same chemical properties. ROR' and R'OR are metamers provided that R and R' are two different alkyl groups

Examples are as shown below:

CH3OC2H5                                   C2H5OCH3

Methoxylethane                              Ethoxylmethane

CH3COOC2H5                                   C2H5COOCH3

Ethylethanoate                                   Methylpropanoate

Pentan-2-one                              Pentan-3-one

Pentan-2-one and Pentan-3-one can be called more of positional isomers that metamers.

Functional Group Isomerism

This type of isomerism occurs between two different organic compounds with different functional group. They do have the same molecular formula But different structural formula which is as a result of difference in their functional groups.

It is obvious that they will have different chemical properties. Alkanoic acid and alkanoate, alkanal and alkanone, alkanol and alkoxyl, alkene and cycloalkane, alkyne and cycloalkane are examples of functional group isomers.

CH3COOCH3                    C3H6O2          C2H5COOH

It should be noted that tautomerism can be referred to as a functional group isomerism. Tautomerism is a phenomenom whereby two organic compounds of the same molecular formular are in a state of dynamic equilibrium, or the process whereby an unstable organic compound is converted to a stable organic compound with the same molecular formular.

Stereoisomerism

In this type of isomerism, the two organic compounds has the same molecular formula But different spatial structures.

In this case the arrangement of elements of the compound in three-dimension differs. It is sub-divided into TWO various types;

·     Geometric isomerism

·     Optical isomerism

Geometric Isomerism

This type of isomerism occurs when there is restrictions in the rotation of Carbon atom somewhere in the molecule.

It is usually explained where there is Carbon to Carbon double bonds (i.e alkenes). It is usually called Cis-trans isomerism. When the attachments to the two Carbon atoms of the Carbon to Carbon double are rotated on the same side, it is usually called cis. But if the attachments rotate on the opposite sides, it is called trans.

     Cis -                    Trans -

It can be explained in dichloroethene, But-2-ene, But-2-enedioic acid, Pent-2-ene and so on.


Cis-1, 2-dichloroethene     Trans- 1, 2-dichloroethene

Cis-But-2-ene               Trans-But-2-ene

Cis-But-2-enedioic acid     Trans-But-2-enedioic acid

Cis-pent-2-ene          Trans-pent-2-ene


Optical Isomerism

This is otherwise called Enantiomerism and hence, optical isomers are also referred to as enantiomers.

The mirror image of a molecule is said to be an optical isomer of its original molecule. For a molecule to be able to undergo optical isomerism, it must be optically active (i.e chiral). A chiral molecule is any molecule that has the ability to rotate a plane polarized light in a clockwise direction or anticlockwise direction. An optically active molecule that rotate plane polarized light clockwisely at an angle of 25o is called a dextrorotatory molecule. While an optically active molecule that rotate plane polarized light anticlockwisely through an angle of 12o is called a Laevorotatory molecule. So, when a dextrorotatory molecule and vice-versa.


Organic Reactions

These are chemical reactions that organic compounds usually undergo. They are as listed below:

·     Combustion reaction               - Substitution reaction

·     Addition reaction                    - Elimination reaction

·     Hydration reaction                    - Esterification reaction

·     Oxidation reaction                    - Reduction reaction

·     Polymerization reaction               - Vulcanization reaction

·     Cracking reaction                    - Fermentation reaction

Combustion Reaction

This requires the burning of organic compounds in the presence of Oxygen in order to form Carbon IV oxide and water in gaseous state (i.e steam). When the organic compound combusted is saturated, there will be no soots are formed as part of the product. The degree of unsaturation is a function of the amount of soot that will be formed.

If Cxffy undergoes combustion reaction, (x + ) moles of Oxygen gas will be required to form x moles of Carbon IV oxide gas and moles of steam. It is as illustrated below:

CxHy + (x + )O2 → xCO2 + H2O

For Alkanes: CnH2n + 2 + (n + ) O2 → nCO2 + H2O

x = n, y = 2n + 2

Hence, CnH2n + 2 + ()O2 → nCO2 + (n + 1)H2O


For Alkenes: CnH2n + (n + ) O2 → nCO2 + H2O + soot

x = n, y = 2n

Hence, CnH2n + ()O2 → nCO2 + (n)H2O


For Alkynes: CnH2n - 2 + (n + ) O2 → nCO2 + H2O + soot

x = n, y = 2n - 2

Hence, CnH2n - 2 + ()O2 → nCO2 + (n - 1)H2O + soot

(i)     CH4(g) + 2O2(g) → CO2(g) + H2O(g)

(ii)     C2H4(g) + 3O2(g) → 2CO2(g) + 2H2O(g) + soot

(iii)     2C2H4(g) + 5O2(g) → 4CO2(g) + 2H2O(g) + soot

(iv)     2C6H6(g) + 15O2(g) → 12CO2(g) + 6H2O(g)

It should be noted that combustion reaction can be written for any hydrocarbon, it is a matter of knowing the values of x and y respectively. And then substitute into the * equation above.

Addition Reaction

This is a reaction of unsaturated organic compounds. For an organic compound to undergo this reaction, it must be unsaturated of which it becomes saturated after the reaction has taken place. Hence, addition reaction is defined as a reaction whereby the double bond or triple bond of an unsaturated compound is being attached by reagent to form saturated product.

This reaction is sub-divided into the following:

·     Hydrogenation(addition of Hydrogen)

·     Halogenation (addition of halogen)

·     Hydrohalogenation (addition of Hydrogenhalide)

·     Addition of hypohalous acid

The three organic compounds that usually undergo addition reaction are alkene, alkyne and Benzene.

(a). Hydrogenation: This requires the addition of Hydrogen to the unsaturated compound to form a saturated product in the presence of metals such as Nickel, Platinum or even palladium as a catalyst.

Alkene requires 1 mole of H2 to form Alkane in the presence of Nickel catalyst.

Alkyne requires 2 moles of H2 to form Alkane in the presence of Nickel catalyst. It is actually a two-stage reaction in which alkene is formed before the alkane.

(i)     C2H4(g) + H2(g) C2H6

(ii)     C2H2(g) + 2H2(g) C2H6

CnH2n 2 + H2O → CnH2n 1OH ᴝ RCHO

e.g

Ethenol(unstable) Ethanal (Stable)

Ethenol and Ethanol are called tautomers since they undergo tautomerism which is defined as the ability of two organic compounds to be at dynamic equilibrium to one another or a process whereby an unstable organic compound is converted to a stable compound which is a functional group isomer.

Dehydration Reaction

This involves the removal of water molecule from an organic compound. It is an elimination reaction. It is usually undergone by the alkanols to form alkenes.

It should be noted that alkanols are classified into two forms:

1.     In terms of the number of functional group (-OH)

2.     In terms of the attaching alkyl groups to the Carbon that bond to the OH

Monohydric alkanol          Dihydric alkanol (glycol)          Trihydric alkanol     

Primary alkanol               Secondary alkanol               Tertiary alkanol


E.g

     Ethanol               Butan-2-ol               3-methylhexan-3-ol

So, dehydration of alkanol requires concentrated H2SO4 as the dehydrating agent and the reaction occur at 180oC.

Ethanol                         Ethane     

Butan-2-ol                         But-2-ene

Esterification Reaction

This is more or less an organic neutralization reaction since it is the reaction between an organic acid i.e alkanoic acid) and an organic base (i.e alkanol) to form an organic salt (i.e ester) and water in the presence of dilute mineral acid as a catalyst. The dilute mineral acid mostly used is dil H2SO4 or dilute HCl.

RCOOH + R'OH RCOOR' + H2O

The reverse process is called Hydrolysis since it requires the addition of water. The esters are known with their fruity odour.

CH3COOH(aq) + C3H7OH(aq) ᴝ CH3COOC3H7(aq) + H2O(l)

Ethanoic acid      Propanol Propylethanoate water

Oxidation Reaction

This requires the addition of Oxygen to an organic compound by using acidified KMnO4 or acidified K2Cr2O7 as the oxidizing agent. The oxidation of alkene requires alkaline KMnO4 which is called Baeyer's Reagent.

Oxidation of Ethene gives Ethan-1, 2-diol as the product.

C2H4 + H2O + [O] CH2(OH)CH2(OH)

Ethene                         Ethan-1, 2-diol

Oxidation of alkanol depends on the type of alkanol in order to determine the product that will be formed.

Oxidation of primary alkanol in excess of acidified KMnO4 gives alkanal as the intermediate product and finally give alkanoic acid.

          

C2H5OH + [o] KMnO4/H+      CH3CHO

Ethanol     -H2O          Ethanal


CH3CHO + [o] KMnO4/H+      CH3COOH

Ethanal     -H2O          Ethanoic acid


But, if the alkanol is in excess, the product is alkanal and that will be the final product.

Oxidation of primary alkanol is different from that of secondary alkanol, because secondary alkanol gives alkanone as the product. Neither the reagent is in excess nor is the alkanol in excess, the final product is alkanone.

     Propan-2-ol                    Propanone

It should be noted that tertiary alkanol doesn't undergo oxidation reaction.

Reduction Reaction

This requires the addition of Hydrogen to an organic compound by using either Sodium tetrahydridoBorate III (NaBH4) or Lithium tetrahydridoAluminate III (LiAlH4) as the reducing agent. Reduction reaction is applicable to Alkanal and Alkanone. Alkanal reduces to a primary alkanol, while alkanone reduces to a secondary alkanol. Hope you can remember that alkanals are aldehydes while alkanones are ketones.

CH3 CHO + 2[H] LiAlH4 CH3 CH2OH

Ethanal               Ethanol

Propanone                         Propan-2-ol

It should be noted that alkanal and alkanone can be differentiated by carrying out tests with Fehling's solution, Tollen's reagent and Benedict's solution. Alkanals give positive test, while alkanones do not show any positive test.


Fermentation Reaction

This is a reaction that breakdown a large organic molecule into a small organic molecule and liberate Carbon IV oxide gas by action of micro-organism. The enzyme zymase is the one that does the breaking down and it is usually gotten from the micro-organism Yeast.

When a palm wine is fermented, it becomes alcoholic. After exposure to air, the Ethanol turns to Ethanoic acid which makes the palm-wine to taste sour.

C6H12O6 2C2H5OH + 2CO2

Glucose       Ethanol

Polymerization Reaction

This is a reaction that requires the coming together of small organic molecules to form a giant organic molecule. The giant compound formed is called the POLYMER, while those small molecules are called MONOMERS.

Polymerization is divided into Addition polymerization and condensation polymerization.

ADITTION POLYMERIZATION: This type of polymerization does not leads to the elimination of a small molecule. In this case, a single product is formed which is the polymer.

Examples: 3C2H2 → C6H6

      Ethyne     Benzene

          

Ethene                    Polythene

Condensation Polymerization

This type of polymerization leads to the elimination of a small molecule such as H2Oor CO2. In this case, the polymer is not the only product.

2C6H12O6 → C12H22O11 + H2O

Monosaccharide Diasaccahride

Also, polymers are sub-divided into two types which are homopolymer and copolymer. In homopolymer, the monomers are all the same. But, in copolymer there are two different types of monomer.

Cracking Reaction

This is a reaction whereby higher alkanes are being converted to a lower alkane as a result of heating or introduction of a catalyst. This reaction can be catalytic or thermal depending on what is required to break the higher alkane to a lower alkane.

C10H22 → C8H18 + C2H4

Decane      Octane

When catalyst is required, it is called catalytic cracking.

It is more expensive But controllable.

When heating is required, it is called Thermal Cracking. It is not controllable But cheap.

Vulcanization Reaction

This is a reaction that requires the burning of rubber in the presence of rubber so as to make it toughen. This process was discovered by an American Scientist called Charles Goodyear. The burning of the rubber in the presence of Sulphur is to increase the elasticity of the rubber. A person who specialise in vulcanizing is called a vulcanizer. During vulcanization C-H is being replaced by C-S to cross-link the bond.
